1.2 — Complete Doctrine Set (22 Active Doctrines)
All 13 doctrines from Parts #1 and #2 remain in full force (001–013). Doctrines 014–018 are permanently retired and reserved. The four new doctrines for Part #3 are:
DOCTRINE-019: CONTEXT EVENTS ARE NON-DETERMINATIVE
  A CONTEXT_EVENT records a claim of operational circumstance.
  It does NOT:
    - Start or stop any clock (detention, dwell, or otherwise)
    - Trigger any system action, state transition, or computation
    - Override, modify, or interact with any other event type
    - Assign fault, liability, or responsibility
    - Validate the factual accuracy of the claimed circumstance
  It EXISTS solely to provide operational context for reviewers.

DOCTRINE-020: CONTROLLED VOCABULARY ENFORCEMENT
  Context event labels MUST be selected from a fixed taxonomy:
    YARD_CONGESTION, EQUIPMENT_BREAKDOWN, DOCK_UNAVAILABLE,
    SAFETY_HOLD, REGULATORY_INSPECTION, WEATHER_INTERRUPT,
    POWER_OR_UTILITY_OUTAGE, SHIFT_CHANGE_DELAY
  No free-text labels. Taxonomy expansion requires a system migration.

DOCTRINE-021: CONTEXT EVENTS DO NOT TRIGGER DISAGREEMENT FLAGS
  Context events are NOT disputable via the driver disagreement mechanism.
  Drivers may add general DRIVER_NOTE annotations but these are NOT linked
  to context events via referenced_event_id.

DOCTRINE-022: EVIDENCELEDGER DOES NOT COMPUTE (CAPSTONE)
  The system records facts, declarations, and context. It does NOT calculate
  dwell time adjustments, detention, demurrage, billing, or any derived metric.
  All policy-based calculations are the responsibility of external systems
  consuming EvidenceLedger’s tamper-proof data as input.
