## 8. Contextual Delay Event Record

Classification: Non-determinative operational context
Nature: Explanatory annotations recorded by facility staff
System Posture: Neutral contextual recorder

### 8.1 Contextual Events Recorded During This Session

| # | Event ID | Label               | Severity    | Timestamp (UTC) | Captured By    |
|---|----------|---------------------|-------------|-----------------|----------------|
| 1 | EVT-002  | YARD_CONGESTION     | OPERATIONAL | 10:41:03        | Facility Staff |

### 8.2 Event Characteristics
  - Event is explicitly contextual, not declarative
  - Event contains no detention start or end signal
  - Event asserts operational condition only, not responsibility
  - Label is selected from a fixed, predefined taxonomy
  - No free-text narrative is attached

### 8.3 System Behavior Declaration
The system recorded the event immutably, preserved the timestamp and actor
role, attached the context label, and maintained chronological order.
The system did NOT: infer delay duration, calculate detention, assign fault,
validate factual accuracy, or escalate consequences.

### 8.4 Relationship to Detention and Liability
Contextual events do not start detention clocks.
Contextual events do not stop detention clocks.
Contextual events do not override paperwork or gate events.
Contextual events cannot be used alone to assert claims.
They exist solely to provide operational context.

### 8.5 Evidentiary Weight Statement
These contextual events represent facility-declared claims of circumstance.
They are preserved for reviewers (courts, lawyers, auditors, insurers).
The system makes no determination about their accuracy or relevance.

### 8.6 Integrity
Each contextual event is append-only, cryptographically hashed, chain-linked,
and visible regardless of later disputes or corrections.
Any disagreement must be expressed through separate annotations or events.
